C. Cornelium] C. Cornelius, who was tr. pl. in B. c. 67, brought on himself the hostility of the senate by the Leges which he proposed. One of his most important Leges was this, that only the Populus should have the power of releasing any person from the obligation of a Lex. The tr. pl. P. Servilius Globulus, who was gained over by the other side, used his veto and resisted the reading of the Lex by the Pmeco, upon which Cornelius read it himself (codicem legisse dicebatur). A great disturbance was raised against the consul C. Piso, who was opposed to Cornelius, and Cornelius dis- missed the meeting.
